<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-409-183  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 409 183.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lasers andamp; Optronics  Jan 1990 v9 n1 p26(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Brunel is on the right track with fiber hybrid sensors. (BrunelCentre for Manufacturing Metrology Dir Barry Jones's work oncommercially viable optical technology) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Weiss, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Brunel Centre for Manufacturing Metrology Dir Barry Jones isdedicated to developing commercially viable optical technology bycombining resonance electrical circuitry with optical signaltransmission and device activation.andP;  Jones says manufacturers arenot yet ready to invest heavily in optical fiber sensors that aretotally separate from current reliable electrical devices,although the technology will likely be used exclusively forinformation recording, transmission and control in the nextcentury.andP;  A small optically powered quartz resonator hybridtemperature sensor with fiberoptic links is described with aquartz oscillator frequency stepped down electrically by a factorof 256 by 1,024.andP;  The group will develop an optical fiber hybridsensing and control system to demonstrate the practicalapplications of the approach; benefits to potential industrialsupporters are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Research and DevelopmentFiber OpticsNew TechniqueTechnologySensorsOptical CommunicationsSignal ProcessingBrunel University.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   An optically-powered quartz resonator hybrid temperature sensor.andO;(chart)Person:    Jones, Barry (research).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>